        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The phrase mostly empty is misleading. An atom is not a tiny hard nucleus inside a vacant shell. Its electron cloud is a spread-out quantum state that fills the atom's volume.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.24,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Bring two pieces of matter together and their electron clouds begin to overlap. Negative charges repel, nuclei and electrons rearrange, and the electromagnetic energy rises.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.6,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "But electromagnetism is only half the quantum story. Electrons are identical fermions. Their complete many-electron wavefunction must be antisymmetric when any two electron labels are exchanged.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transform"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.97,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "The practical consequence is Pauli exclusion: two electrons cannot occupy the same complete quantum state.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.78,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Picture quantum states as seats. One electron can take a seat; a second with the opposite spin can share the same spatial orbital, but an identical spin-orbital is blocked. More electrons must occupy different available states.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.31,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "That stacking prevents all electrons from collapsing into one lowest state. It builds shell structure, gives atoms their characteristic size, and makes ordinary matter occupy volume.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.9,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Important correction: Pauli exclusion is not a new force. There is no extra Pauli-force term hiding in the Hamiltonian.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.36,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Instead, antisymmetry restricts which combined states are allowed. When clouds overlap, electrons must rearrange into costlier states, while Coulomb interactions also change. The required energy climbs sharply.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.18,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Your hand pushes atoms toward the table. Their clouds resist deeper overlap, the energy gradient produces a contact force, and the table pushes back. At everyday pressure, tunneling of an entire hand is effectively impossible.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.95,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "So the honest answer has two parts: electromagnetic interactions provide the forces, and fermionic antisymmetry organizes electrons into states that keep matter extended and costly to compress.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T13:29:31"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. If electrons were bosons and could all pile into the lowest state, what would happen to atomic size, chemistry, and the solidity of matter?",
